p Knight the soft cap for a level 60 character regarding AC is 700!!! there seem to be absolutely no effect in raising AC beyond that number against this type of mob.<br><br>Or it could mean that AC doesn't mean jack <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  I guess further testing should involve a higher level mob with higher ATK.<br><br><br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/uaktarmythmaker.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AktarMythmaker</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fun-In-a-Robe</span><br>  Posts: 641<br> <font color=#330000>(12/31/01 2:09:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/faxiomshift90768frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=222.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The effect of AC</span><hr size=1> I read somewhere that the effect of AC is directly related to a mobs ATK rating.  So if your ac is above the mobs ATK, it will be a &quot;soft cap... so yeah, try that against Trakanon and see if it makes a difference.  Hehe, of course, in order to deal with that test you'd need 10 clerics dedicated to saving you long enough to parse anything. <p><b>Aktar Mythmaker<BR>Sorcerer<br>Axiom Shift</b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/uiumunorn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>IumunoRN</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Power Poster</span><br>  Posts: 54<br> <font color=#330000>(1/1/02 2:25:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/faxiomshift90768frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=222.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The effect of AC</span><hr size=1> The same enchanter made another experiment, this time against a very low blue in Velketor.<br><br>Cantrip (enchanter) vs A crystalline watcher (Velk's Lab)<br><br> NUMBER OF DAMAGE <br>AC hits miss dodge total max min avg <br><br>611 609 238 15 40358 92 22 66 <br><br>710 511 186 16 29909 92 22 58 <br><br>817 433 139 11 23559 92 22 54 <br><br>911* 343 140 07 19154 92 22 55 <br><br><br>Conclusion: The AC soft cap for a level 60 character against normal xp mobs (45-51) is...700. That may be wrong of course, but this is what the data seem to indicate. <br><br>If this is true, then the only difference between a level 60, 700 AC wizard tanking an normal xp mob vs a level 60 warrior with 1400 AC is the HP difference and the defensive skills.<br><br><br><br><br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/ugaryen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Garyen</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.houseofdarklight.netfirms.com/other/g.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Power Poster</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#330000>(1/1/02 7:23:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/faxiomshift90768frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=222.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The effect of AC</span><hr size=1> many similar tests have been done by warriors with very different results. the warrior ac soft cap for old world mobs like a froglok from guk is/was 1000 (which is already higher than that casters result of 700 in kunark). supposedly there is an ac soft cap for kunark, velious, and probably luclin too (these numbers suggest that maybe there is a different cap for each class)... but there's also reason to believe that it all depends upon the attack rating of the mob being tested, as well as many other factors. I personally hate to think of all the factors involved and what's what, but some things are for sure. also, its REALLY hard to compare caster defensive numbers to a tank class' same numbers... there are a lot of differences... saying that all lvl 60 characters are capped at 700ac when tanking a froglok krup knight because of those numbers is jumping to conclusions.<br><br>remember, ac isn't just another separate stat, it's a number that's a compilation of your defensive skill/armors/stats(agi) that is supposed to tell you how good your overall defense is. that's why leveling and building defensive skill will increase your ac, more agi can increase your ac, and any armor with ac points on it will increase your total armor class.<br><br>>>If this is true, then the only difference between a level 60, 700 AC wizard tanking an normal xp mob vs a level 60 warrior with 1400 AC is the HP difference and the defensive skills.>><br><br>there is a difference because the soft cap for the warrior is 1200ac(?) on that first mob. even if both characters were soft capped at 700ac it's still just that, a soft cap - and the additional 700ac past the soft cap should give SOME results however small ;) but these results do give me the impression that maybe some casters AC is possibly soft(hard?) capped a lot lower than warrior's AC for the same mobs.<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/uglayde.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Glayde</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Casual Poster</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#330000>(1/2/02 9:13:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/faxiomshift90768frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=222.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The effect of AC</span><hr size=1> Moo.<br><br>I'm sure the info of these tests would be useful if fighting guk frogs and low blues in velks was practical.<br><br>Those mobs are by no means indicitive of most normal grinding mobs. and certainly not of raid level mobs.<br><br>Tanks should still push AC to the max, with some regards to hps.<br><br>Everyone else should push hps and mana for raids.<br><br><br><br><br><br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/uiumunorn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>IumunoRN</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Power Poster</span><br>  Posts: 56<br> <font color=#330000>(1/2/02 5:57:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/faxiomshift90768frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=222.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The effect of AC</span><hr size=1> Glayde, I posted this because these results seem to indicate that there's a point where AC has no more effect depending on the level of the mob, which is what would seem to be logical. What's more the test I posted was against a krup knight in Sebilis, not guk, a level  49-51 mob. It is indicative of a regular xp mob, though not a raid mob.<br><br>I was also finding interesting the possibility that AC doesn't mean jack for anyone beyond 700. While this does not sound logical, it wouldn't be impossible even if from casual observation everyone seem to agree that AC is important. But remember when everyone believed that agi helped with damage avoidance? Logs proved that there was NO effect from AGI beyond a few points of AC. VI even said that agi helped with dodge while logs showed that the chances to dodge something are entirely skill based.<br><br>What I find disturbing with these parsed results is that the possiblity exist that there's no effect from AC at all beyond 700. Here is the result of a cleric fighting a krup knight, with 911 AC<br><br>Caius (cleric) vs Froglok krup knight<br><br> NUMBER OF DAMAGE <br>AC hits miss dodge total max min avg <br><br>911 222 96 04 19071 139 40 85 <br><br><br>Same results as an enchanter with 911 AC, even though clerics have a defense skill of 200 compared to an 145 for an enchanter. So far no proof that AC has a separate mitigation and damage avoidance factor (Which I never believed anyway)<br><br>Check my next post for a log of an enchanter and a warrior against a mist panther (level 60). You'll find them very disturbing.<br><br><br><br><br><br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/uiumunorn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>IumunoRN</A> at: 1/2/02 6:33:17 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/uthorigarngrim.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Thorigarn Grim</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Power Poster</span><br>  Posts: 159<br> <font color=#330000>(1/2/02 6:01:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/faxiomshift90768frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=222.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The effect of AC</span><hr size=1> To continue what Garyen was saying, if you've noticed that when you put on a piece of armor you get more AC than the rated AC of the armor.  Back in early Beta Verant had AC listed as a blank stat.  They are now displayed as X/1000.  When this was done, they made a statement that AC was actually 2 factors, Hit Avoidance and Damage Mitigation.  Thus by combining them you could actually acheive scores over 1000, which was actually the cap for the individual components of AC.  I personally think that Verant just got lazy when it came to stat generation for gear and fixed the damage mitigation to a set percentage for everything.  One of these days I'll have to do some testing....<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/uiumunorn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>IumunoRN</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Power Poster</span><br>  Posts: 57<br> <font color=#330000>(1/2/02 6:30:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/faxiomshift90768frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=222.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The effect of AC</span><hr size=1> Cantrip vs mist panther<br> NUMBER OF DAMAGE <br>AC hits miss* dodge total max min avg <br><br>613 503 181 14 20266 62 5 40 <br><br>704 363 112 05 12282 62 5 33 <br><br>805 485 151 09 14668 62 5 30 <br><br>911 445 148 10 13334 62 5 29 <br><br><br>Even against a level 60 mob, the soft cap is once again 700, for an enchanter.  At 900 the enchanter is taking about 23 damage per swing when he's not dodging (counting misses)<br><br>Now here's a warrior with 1400 AC<br><br>Damage Received: 9588<br>Opponent(s) DPS Against You: 11.896<br>Average Damage Per Hit Against You: 30.8<br>Hits Against You: 311 / 625 (49.8%)<br>Misses: 224<br>Dodges: 26<br>Parries: 42<br>Ripostes: 22<br><br>Damage Received: 9101<br>Opponent(s) DPS Against You: 10.873<br>Average Damage Per Hit Against You: 28.0<br>Hits Against You: 325 / 643 (50.5%)<br>Misses: 232<br>Dodges: 25<br>Parries: 34<br>Ripostes: 27<br><br>Damage Received: 7956<br>Opponent(s) DPS Against You: 10.496<br>Average Damage Per Hit Against You: 28.0<br>Hits Against You: 284 / 579 (49.1%)<br>Misses: 200<br>Dodges: 28<br>Parries: 43<br>Ripostes: 24<br><br>The warrior is getting hit just as hard when he's not riposting/dodging/parrying, but the panther is missing more. The warrior is taking about 17 damage per attack counting in misses... but with 500 less AC the enchanter is taking  roughly 35% more damage when defensive skills aren't activated. Significative but surprisingly small considering the huge AC difference.<br><br>Here's the same warrior against the mist panther, this time with 1063 AC<br><br><br>Damage Recieved: 9166<br>Opponent(s) DPS Against You: 11.888<br>Average Damage Per Hit Against You: 30.3<br>Hits Against You: 303 / 601 (50.4%)<br>Misses: 200<br>Dodges: 30<br>Parries: 33<br>Ripostes: 35<br><br>Damage Recieved: 8198<br>Opponent(s) DPS Against You: 10.551<br>Average Damage Per Hit Against You: 28.1<br>Hits Against You: 292 / 624 (46.8%)<br>Misses: 245<br>Dodges: 25<br>Parries: 34<br>Ripostes: 28<br><br>About 21 damage per attack ( including misses, excluding dodge/parry/riposte)... very close to an enchanter with 911 AC.. and not much worse than at 1400 AC.<br><br>Conclusion? AC seem to work the same for all classes considering results are consistent for an enchanter, a cleric, and a warrior, 3 classes with a wide difference in defense skill cap.  the soft cap seem to be 700 again for a level 60 character against:<br><br>a level 45ish mob in velketor labyrinth<br>a level 50ish mob in Sebilis<br>a level 60 mist panther in Wakening lands.<br><br>We can't jump to conclusion because  the mist panther is notorious for havign a really low max damage for a level 60 mob, BUT the fact is the results are consistent with 3 different mobs and 3 different classes. The only big jump obsered in any test was from 600 AC to 700 AC. going from 700 AC to 1400 AC is reducing damage taken against these mobs by 33%. Far less than I would have expected.<br><br>So I wouldn't conclude the following YET, but before getting more data I would say that HPS are far more important for survivability  than AC (not for efficiency though), and to a lesser extent defensive skills too because they give a guaranteed miss but they don't seem to negate a large amount of the attacks (10-15% for a level 60 warrior).<br><br>So it COULD be that the idea that casters and rangers die so fast because of their low AC is a myth. Much lesser hit points and to a lesser extent defensive skills would be the overwhelming determining factor.<br><br>You can see the full discussion at:<br><br><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=get_topic&f=9&t=006280">forums.castersrealm.com/c...9&t=006280</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br><br><br><br><br> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/uiumunorn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>IumunoRN</A> at: 1/2/02 6:40:02 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/umournsong1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mournsong1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Power Poster</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#330000>(1/3/02 10:16:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/faxiomshift90768frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=222.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> AC  vs HPs</span><hr size=1> I've been in the tiny minority about this ever since level 20..I think AC is less important than most folks believe.  The most dramatic improvements in survivability and efficiency have always come for Folli when he's gotten a nice increase in HP gear, and I've never really noticed much difference in similar improvements in Folli's AC, even when having to serve as the tank for a XP group.  I guess I'm gratified to see that the numbers above tend to support my intuition or experience.  <br><br>More AC is probably always better then less.  But there is often a choice in gear between raw AC and HPs, and I think people often tilt the balance too much in favor of AC at the expense of hit points (and some other stats).  Raids vs. efficient grinding, and tanks vs other melees vs casters also affect this balance, of course.  HPs soak up damage from spells and breath weapons while AC is often unused for 80 or 90 percent of most character's time.  HPs give your character time to survive until healed or the mob is taunted off / mezzed / dies.  <br><br>It's a fun debate or discussion, in any case.  <br><br><br>Folli &quot;Velium Fire Opal Rings&quot; Fairsong<br><br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/uwaldanhire.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Waldanhire</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Power Poster</span><br>  Posts: 34<br> <font color=#330000>(1/3/02 10:50:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/faxiomshift90768frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=222.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The effect of AC</span><hr size=1> ok  then   following this  my  offense is  high  but defense is  low  can i work defense  with out getting  killed  ( pet duel for a few hrs maybe)   now that  they increased our defense i still  never see it go up i never live if i am in a point where i   am getting whacked  bad enough for it to go up <br><br> ok  whos pet gets a chance to kill the ranger  ( but has a nice controler ) want to  see i f i can  raise defense ) <br><br> btw thannks muno for stats  makes for  some good food for thought.. <p>Waldanhire Fulminator<br>58th  Seasoned Ranger of Tunare  </br><img src=http://www.geocities.com/hm2hines/wallyepic.jpg border="0"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/uiumunorn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>IumunoRN</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Power Poster</span><br>  Posts: 58<br> <font color=#330000>(1/3/02 11:46:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/faxiomshift90768frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=222.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The effect of AC</span><hr size=1> Actually I might have made a mistake that exaggerated the effect of warrior AC. <br><br>I was assuming that a 