ass=m><span class=title> Re: The effect of AC</span><hr size=1> As a rogue I've noticed a significant break point when fighting just about anything.  When my Attack rating hits higher numbers, I am far more efficient and significant landing hits.  <br><br>My theory on this is as follows.<br><br>Attack rating / Armor Class = modifier on the combat table being used by the individual or mob.  Therefor, as soon as your attack rating breaks the AC of the mob you are no longer penalized and may actually gain a bonus on the combat table damage result.  I believe the penalties to be more drastic than the bonusses only based on the changes I see to my damage when buffing classes leave or enter the group.  in most raid environments my attack rating hits about 1320, almost 180pts higher than when I have no buffs that increase attack.  <br><br>The flip side to this is that monsters will gain the same bonus against anything with an AC lower than their attack rating.  If a  froglock in L Guk has an attack of 800, going higher than 800 AC will provide diminishing returns.  This can be tested by taking the same tank against a  lot of different types of mobs and parcing the data.  Personally I will not use a parcer, I just play for fun and have enough numbers to deal with at work.<br><br>Thorigarn/Tornik <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/uiumunorn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>IumunoRN</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>the thinker</span><br>  Posts: 91<br> <font color=#330000>(1/24/02 3:46:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/faxiomshift90768frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=222.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The effect of AC</span><hr size=1> The theory of a PC atk vs a mob AC (or level, or whatever they use to mitigate damage) certainly seem to be true. A significant i